Suriname has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Suriname, see Return to the UK
Entry and borders
These include enhanced medical screening and border closures, which is stopping people travelling into and out of the country and limiting those who wish to leave. See Return to the UK
Local measures
The Government of Suriname have instituted a nationwide curfew between the hours of 2000-0600 as a counter measure to the spread of COVID-19. All international borders are closed (including the ferry to Guyana).
The Jodenbreestraat market in the centre of Paramaribo is closed. Other smaller markets have been assigned specific hours of operation. Nightclubs are closed. Bars and restaurants are only selling food and drink to take out. Licences for tour buses have been revoked. It is forbidden to organise activities of more than 100 people.
Further information
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
